### REST API Blueprint - Integration Tests
### Base URL for the API
@baseUrl = http://localhost:8080/api/v1

### ----------------------------------------
### 1. Health Check (public)
### ----------------------------------------
GET {{baseUrl}}/health
Content-Type: application/json

### ----------------------------------------
### 2. User Registration (returns 202, OTP sent to email)
### ----------------------------------------
# @name register
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "test-otp1@example.com",
    "password": "Test123",
    "username": "otpuser1"
}

### The OTP will appear in the Docker logs (mock email). Copy the 6‑digit OTP.
### Replace <OTP> in the next request with the actual value.

### ----------------------------------------
### 3. OTP Verification (activates account and returns JWT)
### ----------------------------------------
# @name verifyOtp
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/otp/verify
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "test-otp1@example.com",
    "otp": "139408"   // <-- replace with actual OTP from logs
}

### The response contains a JWT token. Copy it to @authToken manually.
@authToken = {{verifyOtp.response.body.$.token}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 4. Login (should now succeed)
### ----------------------------------------
# @name login
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "test-otp1@example.com",
    "password": "Test123"
}

### Alternatively, use the token from OTP verification directly.

### ----------------------------------------
### 5. Get Current User Profile (Protected)
### ----------------------------------------
GET {{baseUrl}}/users/me
Authorization: Bearer {{authToken}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 6. Update User Preferences (Protected)
### ----------------------------------------
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/users/me/preferences
Authorization: Bearer {{authToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "notifications": true,
    "language": "fr"
}

### ========================================
### ADMIN USER FLOW (also requires OTP)
### ========================================

### 7. Admin Registration (returns 202, OTP sent to email)
### ----------------------------------------
# @name adminRegister
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "admin@example.com",
    "password": "admin123",
    "username": "admin"
}

### The OTP for admin will appear in the Docker logs. Copy it.

### 8. OTP Verification for Admin
### ----------------------------------------
# @name adminVerifyOtp
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/otp/verify
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "admin@example.com",
    "otp": "201196"   
}

### The response gives a JWT token for the admin (still as role "user" initially).
### You still need to promote the user to admin in the database.

### 9. Promote admin user in database (run this command after OTP verification)
### docker exec -it rest_api_postgres psql -U postgres -d rest_api_blueprint -c "UPDATE users SET role = 'admin' WHERE email = 'admin@example.com';"

### ----------------------------------------
### 10. Admin Login (after OTP verification and promotion)
### ----------------------------------------
# @name adminLogin
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "admin@example.com",
    "password": "admin123"
}

@adminToken = {{adminLogin.response.body.$.token}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 11. Admin: List all users
### ----------------------------------------
GET {{baseUrl}}/admin/users?limit=10&offset=0
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 12. Admin: Create a new user
### ----------------------------------------
# @name adminCreateUser
POST {{baseUrl}}/admin/users
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "newuser@example.com",
    "password": "newpass123",
    "role": "user",
    "username": "newuser",
    "avatar": null
}

@newUserId = {{adminCreateUser.response.body.$.id}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 13. Admin: Get user by ID
### ----------------------------------------
GET {{baseUrl}}/admin/users/{{newUserId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 14. Admin: Update user
### ----------------------------------------
PUT {{baseUrl}}/admin/users/{{newUserId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "username": "updateduser",
    "role": "admin"
}

### ----------------------------------------
### 15. Admin: Delete user
### ----------------------------------------
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/admin/users/{{newUserId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### ----------------------------------------
### 16. Verify deletion (should return 404)
### ----------------------------------------
GET {{baseUrl}}/admin/users/{{newUserId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### ========================================
### PASSWORD RESET FLOW
### ========================================

### 17. Request password reset (returns 202, token sent to email)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/password-reset/request
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "test-otp1@example.com"
}

### The reset token will appear in the Docker logs (mock email). Copy the token.

### 18. Confirm password reset with the token
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/password-reset/confirm
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "token": "<RESET_TOKEN>",
    "new_password": "NewPass5678"
}

### 19. Login with new password
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "email": "test-otp1@example.com",
    "password": "NewPass5678"
}